WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Good morning. Thank you. It's really, it's great to be here. I've really enjoyed the conference and I'm happy to talk to you today.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:15.000
I want to say a little bit about how I got here, how we as data scientists got here, and then where do we go from here?

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.000
What is a future of data science?

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:26.000
So this is an opinionated talk, and I want to give you a chance to talk back to me, not like during the talk,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:32.000
but we'll do Q&A and I'll be around afterward, so tell me what you think.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:37.000
I'm going to start with my most successful data science project.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:44.000
In 2003, when my wife and I were expecting our first baby, I googled this question.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Are first babies more likely to be late or early or both?

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And what I got at the time was anecdotal evidence.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:02.000
My cousin had two babies and they were both early and therefore I don't know.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
What we need here is data.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And the National Survey of Family Growth has data. This is a survey conducted by the CDC.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.000
It started in 1973. They've done 11 repetitions.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.000
They have more than 100,000 respondents now.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
And for female respondents, they have details on their pregnancies and pregnancy length,

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
including duration in weeks.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:35.000
And so I thought if we're asking this question around week 35,

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:38.000
which is when this question becomes a little bit more pointed,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:44.000
we can ask what is the remaining lifetime or remaining duration of a pregnancy at that time.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And you can see here the blue curve is for first babies

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
and the orange curve is all other babies.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And this is the distribution of total duration in weeks.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And you can see that, in fact, first babies are a little bit less likely to be right at the nominal 59 weeks

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:10.000
and a little bit more likely to be a couple of weeks late.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:18.000
So now, if you Google this question, the first two hits on the page are me.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:27.000
And if you go farther down the page, you'll get this BBC article on the topic, which cites me.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So I am now the world-renowned expert on this topic.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:36.000
How did this happen?

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:41.000
So why am I saying that this is my most successful project?

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.000
Because I took a question from not answered

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:50.000
and I put it over into the answered column of questions.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.000
And this was not hard to do.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:57.000
I needed data, and it was freely available, open data.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Thank you to the NSFG.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Simple methods, basic visualization, no fancy statistics, all free, open software,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
and a venue to make it visible, which was my blog.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
And that's all we need.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:18.000
This is an example of what I hope data science is and can be,

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:28.000
which is a set of tools and processes for answering questions, resolving debates, and making better decisions.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
So that's how I got here.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.000
How did we get here, and where are we going?

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And to think about this, I think the Gartner Hype Cycle will help.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:45.000
If you are not familiar with it, this is the idea that new things, new technologies,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:49.000
go through a sequence of phases with these catching names.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
There's a technological trigger that gets things started.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
There is a peak of inflated expectations, a trough of disappointment,

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.000
the slope of enlightenment, and then a plateau of productivity.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So what is the technology trigger that created data science?

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
I'm going to suggest it's ENIAC.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:23.000
This is the first programmable, electronic, general-purpose digital computer in 1945.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
So how did this create data science?

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Here's my thesis, and here's the first opinionated part of this talk.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Data science exists because statistics as a field missed the boat on computers.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:42.000
Let me explain what I mean by that, especially if we look at statistics education.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Most people, if you take the canonical introductory statistics class,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
you learn the central limit theorem, and you learn a few special cases

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:58.000
where sampling distributions have a nice mathematical gap.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:03.000
And then people graduate from that class, and they encounter data for the first time,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
and they ask for help.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And they go to the Reddit statistics forum,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:14.000
and they ask, which test should I use?

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:19.000
This is the question over and over on Reddit statistics.

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Which test should I use?

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Because their education has given them the idea that all of the problems have been solved.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:30.000
You just have to know which test to use.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
And if you don't, that's your fault.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
That's not true.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
I think the data science approach, the computational approach,

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:42.000
says approximately none of the problems have been solved.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:49.000
What we need is a versatile set of tools to compose the solutions that we need.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
And what is the most versatile tool that we have?

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
A programmable, electronic, general-purpose digital computer.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
So, I want to demonstrate this point,

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
the difference between mathematical statistics and computational statistics,

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
by teaching you all of statistical inference in 10 minutes.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
And we're going to do this by testing the variability hypothesis.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
If you're not familiar with this, it is the idea that in many species,

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:22.000
males are more variable than females on many dimensions.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.000
It is a controversial idea.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:27.000
It has a long and interesting history.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.000
So, if you're interested, do read about that.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
As my example, I'm going to try to use something minimally problematic,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:40.000
and we'll just talk about the difference in height between men and women.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:41.000
We need data.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:44.000
Again, the CDC is here to help us.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
The Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System, the BRFSS,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:55.000
is another repeated cross-sectional sample of adults in the U.S.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:01.000
They get more than 400,000 respondents during each cycle,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:06.000
and it includes self-reported heights and weights.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.000
So, as a warm-up, let's just look at the difference in height between men and women.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
I'm going to do this by resampling.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:19.000
This is one of the core tools of computational statistics.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.000
It's the idea that you take the sample that you actually collected,

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
use it to build a model of the population that you're interested in,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:34.000
and then use that model to generate lots and lots of synthesized samples.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
That's the idea of resampling.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
More specifically, with bootstrap resampling,

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
we're going to do that by drawing from the original sample

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.000
a new sample that is the same size, drawn with replacement.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
And so now let's see what that looks like in code.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.000
It's a lot shorter to say in code than it was for me to say in words.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:56.000
There's what it looks like.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:00.000
It's a function that takes a panda's data frame,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:04.000
and it uses the sample method to generate a new data frame

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
that is the same length, n, and it samples with replacement.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:10.000
So that's it.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:13.000
That's the bootstrap resampling process.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
Now we need a test statistic,

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:19.000
and we're going to start with just height, average height.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
So here's a function now that computes my test stat,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
which is the difference in height between the two groups.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:34.000
It uses the group by method to divide the entire sample by sex

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.000
and then extract the height column,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.000
and then the second line there computes the mean in each group,

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:44.000
and then diff computes the difference between those two means.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:50.000
So it's the difference in means between the heights of two groups.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
The last thing I'm going to do is repeat that a thousand times.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So this list comprehension runs resample a thousand times,

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
so it generates new data frames,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:04.000
and then for each one it computes that test statistic.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Here's what the results look like.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:11.000
This is the distribution of those results.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.000
This is the sampling distribution of the difference in height

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
between men and women,

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
and it looks like men are taller than women on average.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
So you've all learned something this morning.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.000
We can now use that sampling distribution to answer a couple of questions.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:33.000
So one is, how precise is that estimate?

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:37.000
In other words, if we had run this experiment over and over,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:42.000
how much would we expect that estimate to vary from one sample to another?

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
And we can do that by computing a confidence interval

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:51.000
that contains 95% of those iterations that we just computed.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:57.000
And from that we can say men are taller by about 14.43 centimeters.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
I can put a confidence interval on that,

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
and because my sample size is super big,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
the confidence interval is super small.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:08.000
That's the first question.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:13.000
Second question is, if we had collected samples like this over and over,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
is it possible that it could have gone the other way?

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
That in this sample, maybe women would have been taller than men,

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
and not surprisingly, we'll find that that is unlikely.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
We can compute a p-value.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
Here's the function that does it.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
And this is based on an assumption

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:32.000
that the tail of that sampling distribution

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
behaves like a normal distribution.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And in that case, I can use the CDF of the normal distribution right there

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
to compute the probability that that difference we saw

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.000
could have been on the other side of zero.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
In this case, the p-value is super small,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
so we conclude that it is unlikely

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
that we could see a difference that big by chance.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Now, if you know some mathematical statistics,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
and in this group I suspect that you do,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
you've probably looked at this example and said,

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
wait a minute, you just did a difference in mean.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:07.000
That's a t-test.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
We could have done that in one line of code.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
I could have even looked it up in a table.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Why are we doing all this?

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
Well, we didn't really care about the difference in means.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
We really care about the difference in standard deviation

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:23.000
or some other measure of variability.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
So, okay, how are we going to do that?

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
With mathematical statistics,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
we now have to go back to the drawing board and start over.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:32.000
Okay, it's not a t-test.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:37.000
What's the test for comparing the difference in standard deviations?

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:38.000
I don't know.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
We've got to go back to Reddit and find out.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
Whereas with mathematical statistics,

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:47.000
I can take that example that I just showed you,

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
seven lines of code,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
and I'm going to make it do the difference in standard deviation.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:54.000
Like that.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:56.000
It was kind of subtle.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
Let me make that a little clearer.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Here's the difference in means.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
Here's the difference in standard deviations.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.000
This is the nice thing about computational statistics.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.000
I can do any test statistic just as easily.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Here's what that distribution looks like.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:17.000
This is the sampling distribution of the difference in standard deviations.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
And once again, it's precise because my sample size is so big,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
and the p-value is quite small.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
So this is saying that at least as measured by standard deviation,

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
men are more variable than women.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
But maybe standard deviation isn't the right thing to measure

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
because almost any growth process,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
if it makes bigger things,

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
it probably has more variability.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:46.000
So we might be more interested in standard deviation relative to the mean.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:51.000
So maybe we should use the coefficient of variation instead,

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:54.000
because that's the ratio of standard deviation to mean.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.000
So we could go back to the Reddit statistics forum

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
We could go back to the Reddit statistics forum

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:05.000
and ask how to compare coefficients of variation.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
Or again, we can go back to this example

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
and change it so that it looks like that.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
So, not too bad.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
It got a little bit more complicated,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
only because coefficient of variation isn't a built-in function.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
So I had to implement it.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:24.000
But we're still at a grand total of nine lines of code.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.000
And now we can see that the confidence interval is small

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
and the p-value is small.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
So this result is statistically significant.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:37.000
But the difference is really small

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
and probably has no consequences in real life.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:44.000
And it might actually just be the result of some data errors.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
There are suspiciously short and tall people in this dataset.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
So I guess our answer is

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
this dataset doesn't provide much support

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
for the variability hypothesis.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
But that wasn't really the point of this whole thing.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
The point of this is that

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:04.000
mathematical statistics only gets you so far.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:10.000
Really, there is only one way to do hypothesis testing.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And that is this framework.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
This is the there-is-only-one-test framework.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
It always starts with a dataset.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:20.000
And you have to choose a test statistic

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
that quantifies the effect,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
the size of the effect that you are interested in.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
You use the data to create a model of the population.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
We did that by bootstrap resampling,

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
but there are other ways to do it.

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.000
You use that model now to generate lots of simulated datasets.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:42.000
For each dataset, you compute the same test statistic,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
collect all of the results.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
That's your sampling distribution.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
And from that, you can compute a confidence interval

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
or a p-value.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:53.000
That is it.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
That is all of statistical inference in 10 minutes.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
And nine lines of code.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
So here's the analogy I like.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
If you have not watched this channel

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:08.000
where they build Lego mechanisms,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
mathematical statistics is like the level one car

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
that hits the first barrier,

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:17.000
and it gets stuck, and it can't get over it.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:21.000
And computational statistics is like the last car

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
that they build because it's got six wheels and a propeller,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
and it has stilts, and it can climb over anything.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:32.000
So there's my claim.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.000
The technological trigger for data science was computation

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.000
because statistics as a field missed the boat on computation.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
And with apologies to people in the room

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
if you identify as a statistician,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
I'm really talking about the field.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
The field missed the boat,

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
and it missed a lot of other boats.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:57.000
So I think that's why data science came to be.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
And now the question is,

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
have we hit the peak of expectations?

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
Are we in the trough of disillusionment?

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:06.000
Where are we here?

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
So for the peak of expectations,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:14.000
I want to nominate 2009 to 2012

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:18.000
In 2009, we got the Netflix Prize.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.000
And then in 2010, the first iteration of Kaggle,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:26.000
which turned machine learning into a spectator sport.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
In 2011, we got Moneyball,

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:34.000
which turned spectator sports into machine learning.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
Coursera turned machine learning

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
and made it available to everybody.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
And then in 2013, everybody who graduated

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
got the sexiest job of the 21st century,

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:54.000
which I'm going to nominate as the peak of inflated expectations.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:55.000
And when we look at it now,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
it's kind of like the peak of cringe.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
So if that was the peak,

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:05.000
what about the trough of disillusionment?

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:10.000
I'm going to nominate 2016 to 2018 as the trough.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:15.000
2016, Kathy O'Neill introduced us all

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
to the dark side of big data.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:22.000
ProPublica got us thinking about

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
algorithmic fairness and criminal justice.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.000
And famously, data scientists failed to predict

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
the outcome of the 2016 election.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
Now that's not exactly correct,

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:36.000
but that is how people remember it.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:41.000
2017, from former executives at Facebook,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.000
we got some of the first evidence of the harms of social media.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:52.000
We got alarms about facial recognition, fairness, and race.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:58.000
We got warnings about algorithms and fairness and gender.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:05.000
We learned that Cambridge Analytica had been misusing Facebook data.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
We learned that Google had been misusing medical data.

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
And just to cap it all off,

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:18.000
we learned that machine learning is ruining spectator sports.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
So that was not great.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:26.000
And I think that's how we ended up where we are right now

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
in the trough of disillusionment.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:31.000
So where do we go from here?

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:33.000
How do we climb the slope of enlightenment?

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
And what does the plateau of productivity look like?

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:41.000
So I want to suggest two things

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.000
that make me optimistic about where we go from here.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
One that makes me nervous,

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:49.000
and then I have a plea for what you can all do

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
to help us get up that slope.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.000
So here's one thing that makes me feel good.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:58.000
In 1985, we had some of the first data journalism.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:01.000
The USA Today started publishing infographics,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
including this hard-hitting piece

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.000
about which parts of laundry people really dislike doing.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:14.000
In 2015, The Upshot published this,

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:18.000
which is a three-dimensional interactive representation

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
of the yield curve,

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:24.000
one of the most notoriously difficult ideas in economics.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:29.000
Now, I'm not sure I still understand the yield curve,

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
but I really appreciate their optimism about their audience.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:39.000
Which I think is a real thing.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:43.000
I think data journalism is sneakily improving

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:47.000
the level of data literacy in general.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.000
So I really think that's good.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:53.000
They are also complementing the ability of governments

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:56.000
to generate data and share that data.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
Just as two small examples,

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:03.000
The Washington Post now has a better database of gun deaths

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:06.000
than the FBI does.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:10.000
And the New York Times has a better dataset of traffic safety

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:14.000
than the Department of Transportation does.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:15.000
So these are good things.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
I think we're improving data literacy,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:22.000
and the availability of data is continuing to grow and grow.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:24.000
Those are all good.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:26.000
Here's the thing I'm worried about,

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.000
and this comes from the General Social Survey.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
If you are not familiar with it,

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.000
it is a really great source of data.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:39.000
They have been doing a repeated cross-section of adults in the U.S.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.000
since the 1970s.

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:46.000
They have a total now of more than 70,000 respondents.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
And one of the questions that they have asked

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:52.000
during every cycle since 1972 is this one.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:57.000
Taken all together, how would you say things are these days?

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:02.000
Would you say that you are very happy, pretty happy, or not too happy?

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:06.000
So I grabbed that data, and I have plotted it over time.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:11.000
This is the fraction of people who said very happy.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:15.000
It was in the mid-30s when the survey started.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
It was declining slowly,

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:22.000
and then around 2010 started to decline a bit more quickly.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:25.000
Now, if you look at that over time, it does not look great,

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.000
but it's a relatively slow decline.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:31.000
Let me show you now what that looks like by year of birth.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:34.000
This is the fraction of people who say that they are very happy

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:40.000
grouped by what year they were born in.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:43.000
So for people born in the 1880s,

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
because this data set goes back a way.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:47.000
They were very old when they were interviewed,

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.000
but they were pretty happy.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:52.000
It was declining for a while,

00:21:52.000 --> 00:21:55.000
and it has been declining very steeply now

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:02.000
for people born in the 80s, 90s, and 2000s.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:07.000
This is not just because we are interviewing them when they are young.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:10.000
And to see that, let me show you this,

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
and this takes some unpacking.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:14.000
This is now grouped by decade of birth.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:19.000
So each line represents one decade of birth from the 1890s

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:21.000
up to the bottom right-hand corner.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
Those are the people who were born in the 2000s,

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:29.000
and following them over time, over the years of the survey.

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:31.000
So there's a lot going on.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:34.000
Things kind of go up and down.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:38.000
For many groups, things have been declining recently,

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:41.000
but the noteworthy thing in the lower right-hand corner there

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:44.000
is that people born in the 90s and 2000s

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:53.000
are more unhappy now than any previous generation at any age.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.000
So why? Why is that happening?

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:59.000
It's complicated. It's always complicated.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
There are going to be many factors.

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.000
I want to talk about just one of them,

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.000
which seems likely that at least part of this

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:13.000
is excessive consumption of relentlessly negative media.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:16.000
Now, negativity bias is not new.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:20.000
There has always been negativity bias in the media

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.000
and fundamentally in our heads.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:26.000
In our psychology, we have a built-in negative bias,

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.000
but the pattern of consumption is a new thing.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:33.000
We have a new word for it, which is doomscrolling.

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:38.000
Spending too much time reading large quantities of media,

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:43.000
especially negative media.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:45.000
So from a data science point of view,

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:48.000
I think this is a data bias problem.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:51.000
It is a bias in our media diet,

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:55.000
which suggests that data could be an antidote

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:58.000
or at least a partial solution to the problem.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:01.000
Now, the world champion of that idea,

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:04.000
that data can be an antidote to negativity,

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:06.000
was Hans Rosling.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:09.000
This is his famous video showing a bubble graph

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:12.000
of world development in the last hundred years

00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:17.000
as a function of income and life expectancy.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:20.000
Out of curiosity, how many people have seen this video?

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:23.000
Okay, a lot. I thought so.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:26.000
If you have not, I have four minutes and 47 seconds

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:29.000
that you are really going to enjoy.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.000
If you have not read Hans Rosling's book,

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:36.000
I recommend this very strongly.

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:40.000
This is the antidote to a lot of incorrectly negative beliefs

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:43.000
that many people have about the world.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:46.000
That is from 2018, so it is pretty current.

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:49.000
But if you want the most up-to-date data,

00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:53.000
Our World in Data is the current champion of this idea.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:56.000
They do research and data to make progress

00:24:56.000 --> 00:24:58.000
against the world's largest problems.

00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:01.000
And if you explore their site,

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.000
you will see lots of graphs where good things

00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:07.000
go up and to the right, like life expectancy,

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:11.000
and bad things like poverty go down and to the right.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.000
So check that out. I think you'll enjoy it.

00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:17.000
And what you'll find is that on long-term trends,

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.000
almost everything is getting better.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:22.000
Now, people don't know this, and I want to do an experiment.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:24.000
This is from Gapminder.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:27.000
This is the same group that Hans Rosling started.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:30.000
They have a lot of tests that you can take

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:33.000
to see if your perception of the world is accurate.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:35.000
And I'm going to give you one of them.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:38.000
So, how did the number of deaths per year

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:41.000
from natural disasters change over the last 100 years?

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:44.000
Take a second.

00:25:44.000 --> 00:25:47.000
More than doubled. Remained about the same.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:49.000
Decreased to less than half.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.000
More than doubled. Raise your hand.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.000
Stayed about the same.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:57.000
Decreased to less than half.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:00.000
Okay. If you said that it decreased to less than half,

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:03.000
you are correct.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:06.000
And here's the data from Our World in Data.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:09.000
This is the raw number of deaths

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:12.000
from natural disasters going back to 1900.

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:15.000
And depending on when you start and how you compute the difference,

00:26:15.000 --> 00:26:20.000
it has declined by a factor of 5 or 10 in that time.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:23.000
At the same time, world population has gone up

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
by about a factor of 5.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:28.000
So, as a rate, this has gone down substantially.

00:26:28.000 --> 00:26:31.000
This is good news.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:33.000
People do not know this good news.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:37.000
When people take these quizzes, they do less well than chance.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:40.000
84% of people got this wrong.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:42.000
There were only three choices.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.000
33% should have got it right.

00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:46.000
66% should have got it wrong.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:48.000
84% is too many.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:51.000
So, people don't know this.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:55.000
I gave one of these quizzes to my data science class.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:59.000
I had the students take the quiz and then write some reflections on it.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
This is the Google survey.

00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
I don't expect you to read all of this,

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:06.000
but I want to draw your attention to one word

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:09.000
that appeared in almost every response.

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:12.000
I was too pessimistic.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:15.000
And one person just wrote, I'm a pessimist.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:18.000
And I want to tell you what I told them.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.000
You are not a pessimist.

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:25.000
You have been misled by a relentlessly negative media diet.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:30.000
On long-term trends, almost everything is getting better.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.000
I have found that when I say that, people get angry.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:39.000
And my conclusion is, we need to say three things at the same time.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.000
On long-term trends, almost everything is getting better.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:46.000
And we still have serious problems to solve.

00:27:47.000 --> 00:27:54.000
And our history of solving problems suggests that we can solve these new ones too.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:59.000
And when I say that, yes, I'm including climate change.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:02.000
So, where I think we are on climate change,

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:05.000
we have not responded as quickly as we should have.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:08.000
We're still not doing everything we should be doing.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:13.000
But many environmental trends are already going in the right direction.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:18.000
And there are paths between now and the end of the century

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:23.000
toward a stable, healthy environment and a good quality of life for everybody on the planet.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.000
So, we are not doomed.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:29.000
But a lot of people think we are.

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:34.000
If you think we're doomed, or someone in your life thinks we're doomed,

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:36.000
please give them this book.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:39.000
I don't have a chance here to make a complete case

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:42.000
about where we are here.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:47.000
But Hannah Ritchie, who is not coincidentally a researcher at Our World in Data,

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:51.000
this book, I think, makes the case really well.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:56.000
Get a copy, read it out loud to somebody under 30.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:04.000
So, negativity bias, I think, is a serious threat to our well-being

00:29:04.000 --> 00:29:09.000
because it undermines our ability to address the important problems that we need to address.

00:29:09.000 --> 00:29:12.000
So, finally, here is my plea.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:17.000
Here is what I would like you all to do to help us get out of this trough of disillusionment

00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:20.000
and onto the plateau of productivity.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:25.000
First, stop telling kids they'll die from climate change.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.000
Second, stop reading the news.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
This is the other book I want to recommend.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
The title says it all.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:36.000
But if you have trouble mustering the strength to stop reading the news,

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:39.000
this book might help.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:44.000
Last thing, use data to understand the world better

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.000
so that we know how to make the world better.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:51.000
There's a lot of data out there.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:52.000
And I'll tell you a secret.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:57.000
A lot of the organizations that generate open data sets,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:59.000
and especially government agencies,

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:02.000
have enough resources to make the data set and publish it,

00:30:02.000 --> 00:30:06.000
and often not a lot of resources to do much with it.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:09.000
So, when you're the first person to go into one of these data sets

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:12.000
and really look around and explore,

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:15.000
you will inevitably find interesting things,

00:30:15.000 --> 00:30:18.000
like first babies are more likely to be late,

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:22.000
or things that are more important than that.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:26.000
So, take advantage of the data that's out there.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:31.000
And this group in particular has all the tools and processes

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:36.000
that you need to answer questions, resolve debates,

00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:38.000
and make better decisions.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:40.000
It's the tools of open science.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:43.000
And let me turn that sideways so we can read it.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:48.000
Open data, open source software, open methodology,

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:50.000
open peer review, open access,

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:56.000
and especially from my point of view, open educational resources.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:30:58.000
So, I want to end on that,

00:30:58.000 --> 00:31:01.000
because it's one of the things that I work on.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.000
I'll give you a few links

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:07.000
and credit for some of the resources that I've used.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:10.000
If you are interested in that first baby example,

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.000
that is from ThinkStats.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:16.000
And the third edition is what I'm working on right now.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
It's available free at that link.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:21.000
I'll also give you another chance to get these slides

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:24.000
so that you can get those links.

00:31:24.000 --> 00:31:25.000
The data there, as I said,

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:31.000
is from the National Survey of Family Growth run by the CDC.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:34.000
The resampling example, if you're interested in that,

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:38.000
that is from Elements of Data Science, also available free.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:45.000
And all of that data was from the BRFSS, also from the CDC.

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:47.000
Finally, that happiness example

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:52.000
is based on Chapter 10 of Probably Overthinking It.

00:31:52.000 --> 00:31:57.000
And that data is from the General Social Survey.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:01.000
Last thing, all of the notebooks are available.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:04.000
Those links will take you to the notebook running on Colab,

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.000
so if you want to replicate anything I did

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:10.000
or run your own experiments, you can do that.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:12.000
And as of Monday,

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:17.000
I learned enough R to translate my Python examples into R.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:21.000
So if you want to see the variability example in R,

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:22.000
it's there.

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.000
This is, I will admit, the first R program

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:28.000
that I wrote beyond Hello World,

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:33.000
and I am sharing it with all of you to do a code review.

00:32:33.000 --> 00:32:39.000
So I would like to hear what you think about my first attempt.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:42.000
So, I feel like I've had my chance to talk.

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:45.000
Here are five ways that you can get in touch with me

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:47.000
if you want to talk back,

00:32:47.000 --> 00:32:50.000
but we also have a chance to take some questions,

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.000
and again, you can grab the slides

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:55.000
using either that link or the QR code.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:59.000
So, questions?

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:08.000
Thank you.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.000
Thanks for a really inspiring talk, Alan.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.000
So, again, if you've got questions,

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:15.000
you can ask them on the Slido link from the lab,

00:33:15.000 --> 00:33:19.000
and we've got a few coming in already.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:24.000
Okay, a lot coming in already.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:28.000
Okay, two, we're kind of starting at the beginning of the talk.

00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:32.000
So, two questions kind of related about bootstrapping.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:35.000
First of all, like survey data,

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.000
you know, it's really important to account

00:33:37.000 --> 00:33:39.000
for the sampling design and the weights,

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:41.000
and what about the case where you're looking

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:44.000
at smaller data sets with heavier tails?

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
Like, where do you kind of draw the line

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:50.000
between computational statistics and mathematical theory?

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:51.000
Yes, all good questions.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:54.000
So, the first one about the sampling design,

00:33:54.000 --> 00:33:56.000
I actually cut that from the slide,

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:58.000
but it is in the notebook.

00:33:58.000 --> 00:34:02.000
You'll see the BRFSS uses stratified sampling,

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:05.000
so I had to correct for that by using the sampling weights

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:08.000
as part of the bootstrap process,

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:11.000
and that all I had to do was change the sample method

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
to take an additional parameter,

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:15.000
which is the sampling weights.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.000
So, that's one of the nice things about bootstrap

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:23.000
is that kind of re-weighting is super easy to do.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:24.000
With small samples,

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:27.000
you do run into the Achilles heel of bootstrapping,

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:29.000
which is data diversity.

00:34:29.000 --> 00:34:30.000
If you have a small sample,

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:32.000
and you draw new samples from it,

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:34.000
the new samples will just all look the same,

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:38.000
and you won't see enough diversity in the results.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:39.000
And in that case,

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:42.000
one option is to switch to a parametric bootstrap,

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:46.000
where instead of just doing sampling with replacement,

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:47.000
you take your data,

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:49.000
you build a model of the population,

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:52.000
but the model now is a parametric model,

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:54.000
and so it has some smoothness to it,

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.000
and now when you draw samples,

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:58.000
those samples will be continuous and diverse

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:01.000
in all the ways that we want.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:02.000
So, where do I draw the line?

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:03.000
I really don't.

00:35:03.000 --> 00:35:07.000
I use computational stats for everything.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:09.000
One concept I learned about recently,

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:10.000
and maybe you've heard of too,

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:13.000
is this idea of the bitter lesson.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:15.000
This is an idea from,

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:16.000
and I'll probably paraphrase it incorrectly,

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:19.000
but from computer science and AI,

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:23.000
that simple methods that use computation

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:26.000
end up winning regardless over time,

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:28.000
and it felt to me like that's what you're really saying

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:29.000
about the bootstrap.

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:30.000
It's a simple method.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:32.000
It requires computation,

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:33.000
but over time,

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:36.000
computation continues to get better and better,

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:38.000
and we don't have to worry about deriving

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:41.000
all these special cases.

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:42.000
Yeah, really interesting.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:43.000
Would you say the name again?

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:45.000
The bitter lesson.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:46.000
Ah, okay.

00:35:46.000 --> 00:35:47.000
I can send you a link.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:48.000
Please.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:52.000
That's a cool idea.

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:53.000
Okay, next question.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:56.000
I think this question possibly comes from a pessimist.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:57.000
I'm going to stay there.

00:35:57.000 --> 00:35:59.000
I can cure you.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:02.000
How do you suggest we calibrate our worldview

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
when you account for Simpson's paradox,

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:06.000
where all of these large trends are positive,

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:09.000
but if you break them down into smaller categories,

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.000
they all go the opposite way?

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:14.000
I think that's possible in theory,

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.000
but I don't think I've seen examples of it.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:19.000
One of my examples looking at poverty globally,

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:22.000
the global trend was declining poverty,

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:25.000
and then when you divide it up by region,

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:28.000
all of the regions are negative.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:29.000
There will always be exceptions.

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.000
There will be short-term reversals,

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.000
and there will be specific places and times

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:37.000
where things are not necessarily positive,

00:36:37.000 --> 00:36:39.000
but the long-term trends are positive.

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:44.000
I have not seen examples of Simpson's paradox there.

00:36:45.000 --> 00:36:48.000
Thank you.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.000
What was the hardest part of writing your first R script?

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.000
Oh, you know what the answer is going to be.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:57.000
It was fixing my environment.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
I had an old, broken installation of R,

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:04.000
and it took me an hour and a half to get it fixed.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:05.000
It's not Python.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:08.000
Most people don't have an environment.

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:14.000
Same complaint about Python all the time, sure.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.000
What do you think that statistics educators need to do

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:17.000
to get on the boat,

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
and what do data science educators need to do

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:23.000
to make sure their students stay statistically responsible

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:25.000
and literate?

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
Yeah, what do educators need to do to get on the boat,

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.000
and sorry, second part?

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:30.000
So statistics educators,

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:33.000
how do we get them moving towards the computational side,

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:36.000
and I think while still helping data science educators

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
to kind of cultivate that skepticism

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:41.000
that statistics is so good at.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
Right.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:44.000
Well, so one piece of this,

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:48.000
a lot of universities are creating data science programs,

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:50.000
and they're going about it in a way

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.000
that is how universities work,

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.000
which is that they get a bunch of computer scientists

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:57.000
and a bunch of statisticians

00:37:57.000 --> 00:37:59.000
and try to make them play together,

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:00.000
and the assumption is that

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:03.000
that is somehow going to be data science,

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.000
and I think that doesn't work.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:08.000
I think data science is a different thing from both of those,

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:11.000
and starting with people

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:15.000
who are professionally attached to those identities

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:18.000
is probably not the right starting place,

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:22.000
so I think if you're going to do data science education,

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:25.000
you need data scientists.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:31.000
Interesting. Thank you.

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:33.000
This is an interesting one.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.000
What do you sacrifice in your life

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.000
to be so prolific in your output?

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:42.000
I was amazed by all the books you've done.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:45.000
Oh, thank you.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:48.000
I really don't feel like it's a sacrifice at all.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:49.000
I really enjoy the work.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:50.000
I look forward to it.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
I make consistent progress,

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.000
so I don't feel like I have to work

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:59.000
in sudden bursts of staying up all night.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:02.000
I don't do all-nighters, that kind of thing,

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:07.000
but I don't think I'm neglecting other parts of my life.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:10.000
Is your wife in the audience?

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:15.000
My wife is, in fact, here, so we can ask.

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:19.000
I will also say, as someone who's written quite a few books, too,

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:21.000
I find that, for me personally,

00:39:21.000 --> 00:39:23.000
it's that writing regularly,

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:26.000
just making that steady progress,

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:30.000
and that advice I've given to everyone who wants to write a book,

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:33.000
so far, no one has successfully followed that advice.

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.000
It's a very simple idea,

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.000
but it's very, very hard to do.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:41.000
But I think at some point,

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:43.000
it just becomes your default.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
I personally feel, when I'm not writing a book,

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:48.000
like something is missing from my life.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.000
I don't know if you feel the same.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:53.000
For me, it's the most relaxing kind of work that I do.

00:39:53.000 --> 00:39:55.000
So if I'm stressed about something,

00:39:55.000 --> 00:40:00.000
taking some time to focus and do some writing is a relief.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:08.000
Humans and governments often only seem to act on big challenges,

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
like climate change,

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:13.000
when the challenge seems like a crisis.

00:40:13.000 --> 00:40:17.000
How do we inspire change without a sense of doom?

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:21.000
Yeah, and I do think that's part of how we got to climate numerism,

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:26.000
which is, climate denialism was such a problem for so long

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:30.000
that people felt like they had to turn up the heat, metaphorically,

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:33.000
and insist more and more strongly,

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:36.000
this is a crisis, we need to react now,

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:39.000
and we've almost gone too far.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:42.000
So yeah, how do you get people engaged

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:46.000
without invoking that overshoot?

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:49.000
That is a really hard question, I don't know.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:53.000
To me, I think about the year 2000 kind of crisis,

00:40:53.000 --> 00:40:56.000
where everyone was like, oh my god, it's going to be terrible,

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.000
and then nothing happened,

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.000
and so people were like, oh, it was overblown.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:04.000
But you can't tell whether or not it was overblown,

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:06.000
because people did all this work to make sure.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.000
It's this problem that,

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:11.000
if you fix a problem before people experience it,

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:14.000
they don't appreciate you as much.

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:17.000
This is a problem in software development as well, right?

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:20.000
If you remove people from having to feel pain,

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:22.000
they don't appreciate you.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:25.000
You have to make them feel pain and then take it away,

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:27.000
and then they appreciate you.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:30.000
This is not a technique I use, I'm just saying.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.000
So I think, yeah, that's a good analogy.

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:35.000
But it also reminds me,

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:38.000
we do have a long history of actually solving problems.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:41.000
And so a recent, relatively current one

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:44.000
is the hole in the ozone layer.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:47.000
In the 1980s, that was the big crisis.

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:51.000
And when was the last time you even heard anybody say ozone layer?

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:54.000
And the reason is that we have largely solved that problem.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:58.000
We banned most of the chemicals that were causing the damage.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
The ozone hole has been closing for decades,

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:04.000
and will probably completely close by the end of the century.

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.000
So we actually got together.

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:11.000
The Montreal Protocol, I think, was the treaty,

00:42:11.000 --> 00:42:13.000
the international treaty.

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:18.000
I think 190 countries signed on to it and got it done.

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:23.000
Yeah, again, it's so easy to miss the pain that's gone away.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.000
Yeah.

00:42:27.000 --> 00:42:31.000
How do you reconcile a desire to be an informed and engaged citizen

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:35.000
with advice that says to read less news to be happy?

00:42:35.000 --> 00:42:37.000
So I've started doing this.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:40.000
Within the last year, I consume almost no news media.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:43.000
I do read The Economist, so that's an exception.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:46.000
And what I've found is that if something is important enough

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:50.000
that I really need to know it, I will hear about it.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:52.000
Yeah.

00:42:59.000 --> 00:43:01.000
Here's a good one.

00:43:01.000 --> 00:43:04.000
Should we distinguish data science from science in general?

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:08.000
Is there a meaningful distinction?

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:09.000
Yeah.

00:43:09.000 --> 00:43:12.000
So, you know, is data science just doing science?

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:15.000
Because when you're doing science, you're almost always working with data,

00:43:15.000 --> 00:43:17.000
and you are using that data to answer questions,

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:20.000
resolve debates, and make better decisions.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
So, yeah, I think there's an argument there.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:25.000
That last part, though, might be a difference,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:28.000
which is that science is usually about creating knowledge

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:32.000
and not necessarily designing things or making decisions.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:36.000
So maybe what that means is that data science is actually broader

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:39.000
than science because it also includes those elements.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:40.000
Yeah.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.000
Makes sense.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:46.000
Here.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:49.000
How do you reconcile optimism against an overwhelming amount

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:52.000
of climate scientists that feel we are approaching

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:55.000
an unreconcilable ecological disaster

00:43:55.000 --> 00:43:58.000
and whose historical recommendations have a bias

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:01.000
towards being overly optimistic already?

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:05.000
So, yes, the one way that I could be wrong,

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:07.000
if we look at long-term trends and we say,

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:11.000
hey, things are going well, if we keep doing what we're doing...

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:14.000
Because, you know, those long-term trends didn't happen automatically.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:16.000
We did things that made them happen.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:18.000
So if we keep doing what we're doing

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:21.000
and keep solving problems as we confront them,

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:24.000
we should continue to make progress.

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:27.000
The exception to that would be something like a tipping point

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:32.000
where we really do cross a line that we can't go back over.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:35.000
And there are some scenarios in climate predictions

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.000
where that is a possibility.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:40.000
My understanding of current climate science

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.000
is that we don't have strong evidence

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:48.000
that any of those are imminent or high-probability events.

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:50.000
So I am still going on the assumption

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.000
that if we keep doing what we're doing,

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.000
things will continue to get better.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:57.000
But something like that could make me wrong.

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:00.000
So you talked about...

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:04.000
You provided us a hypothesis that doom-scrolling

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:09.000
is the leading cause of lower reported happiness in younger people.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.000
Do you have any data to support that hypothesis?

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:16.000
So, yes, I claimed that consumption of negative media

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:19.000
is one of the causes of unhappiness.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:22.000
I have read articles to support that.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:24.000
There are books like Anxious Minds,

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:26.000
and a few others.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:29.000
I will get you some more references.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:32.000
So I haven't worked with that data myself,

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.000
but I have read enough books

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:38.000
to make me think that it is a plausible hypothesis

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:40.000
as at least part of the problem.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:43.000
I'm not trying to assert that I know for sure

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.000
that it is all of the problem.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:47.000
Not that.

00:45:47.000 --> 00:45:49.000
This next question is kind of related,

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:51.000
but, like, how do you know

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:53.000
This next question is kind of related,

00:45:53.000 --> 00:45:54.000
but, like, how do you...

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:57.000
If you're going to ignore the news,

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:00.000
how do you avoid getting stuck in a trough of toxic positivity

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:04.000
where you're just going to believe everything is fine?

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:07.000
Is there a trough of toxic positivity?

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:13.000
I think the real qualifier is just the assumption

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:15.000
that just because things are getting better,

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:18.000
that doesn't mean it will continue to happen automatically.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:22.000
We still need to do the things that make that happen.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:25.000
What we're depending on is the ongoing effort

00:46:25.000 --> 00:46:28.000
of everybody working on these problems

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:32.000
and the innovation that will create the new things

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:34.000
that will continue to make progress.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:41.000
So I think that would be not the unwarranted optimism

00:46:41.000 --> 00:46:44.000
that just assumes that everything magically is going to get better.

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.000
So not that.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:49.000
I think there are also other ways of learning about the world

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:52.000
than, like, following the news too closely.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:55.000
Like, you can read books.

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:57.000
You can, like, read articles.

00:46:57.000 --> 00:47:00.000
Like, the news cycle is very rapid and designed

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:02.000
to, like, keep you addicted.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.000
Yeah.

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:07.000
Yeah, there are ways to kind of try and escape that.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:09.000
Yeah, longer-term media.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:12.000
As a book author, I recommend that you read books.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:14.000
Yeah.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:19.000
Yeah.

00:47:23.000 --> 00:47:27.000
How do you account for the shifting baseline syndrome

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:29.000
regarding the definition of quality of life?

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:33.000
I think this is sort of related to the, like, hedonic treadmill as well.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:35.000
Like, also, as things get better over time,

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:37.000
you expect them to be better,

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:39.000
and then when they get worse,

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:42.000
even if they were better than they were before, it still feels bad.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:44.000
Yes.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:47.000
The shifting definition of poverty is a good one,

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:50.000
and it's in some sense a sign of progress.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:52.000
You know, at some point in time,

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:55.000
you pick a threshold, and then you target that.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:47:57.000
And if things go well,

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:59.000
eventually that target becomes obsolete,

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:02.000
and you aim for a higher threshold.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.000
So that's good. That's a sign of progress.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:07.000
It just means you have to be consistent in your definitions

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:10.000
when you're doing the data analysis.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:13.000
But there was a second part there that was a little more challenging.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
Remind me.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:21.000
I think that question got wiped off already,

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
so I've already forgotten that, too.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.000
Yep.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:28.000
And that is why you should not ask two-part questions.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:34.000
What about the negativity bias?

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.000
Is it truly the—

00:48:36.000 --> 00:48:38.000
Do you think it's the fault of the media

00:48:38.000 --> 00:48:42.000
or the reader's behaviors interacting with the negative news more?

00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.000
It's definitely both.

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:48.000
So negativity bias is one of our cognitive errors.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:51.000
It seems to be just built into human beings.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.000
And in some sense, it makes sense

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.000
that we should focus a little bit more

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:58.000
on things that are broken and need to be fixed.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:01.000
So it's potentially adaptive in that sense.

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:04.000
But now, if you put that brain into an environment

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:07.000
where it gets that constant feedback,

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:10.000
I think that's where the hazard comes from.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:15.000
Because the producers of news have figured out

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:19.000
that people will pay more attention to negative news than positive news,

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.000
so that's what they feed us.

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:26.000
And I think that's the feedback cycle that is the source of the problem.

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:30.000
I will say that I think data science is partly to blame there

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:34.000
because now news organizations are very carefully tracking

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:36.000
what are people reading and responding to.

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.000
And they want to serve their customers.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:40.000
They want to make money.

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.000
They want to give the people what they want.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:45.000
And that can easily lend itself to this vicious cycle

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:48.000
where they're like, well, what are people reading the most?

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:51.000
And if you're not careful, that's like listicles

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:57.000
and other things like the secrets that so-and-so doesn't want you to know.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:01.000
There is this balance between how do you survive as an organization

00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:04.000
in the short term, how do you make money

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:07.000
while still achieving your mission in the long term

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:10.000
and not being too distracted by what the data is telling you.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:14.000
I think there's sort of a really interesting tension there

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:17.000
that you want to pay attention to the data and listen to the data,

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.000
but you can't just follow it.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.000
You can't just A-B test everything

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:24.000
and then do whatever the maximizing your revenue

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:27.000
or whatever you want to maximize it.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:28.000
Yeah, yeah.

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:32.000
It's a challenge.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:36.000
How effective is data in combating negativity bias

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:39.000
in the media environment where people can just curate their feeds

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:41.000
to tell them what they want to hear?

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.000
Do you find people are receptive to this data

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:46.000
that goes against everything social media is selling them?

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:48.000
No.

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:52.000
No, I mentioned this very often when I say on long-term trends,

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:55.000
almost everything is getting better.

00:50:55.000 --> 00:50:58.000
Very often people really do react angrily,

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:01.000
and part of it is cognitive dissonance,

00:51:01.000 --> 00:51:04.000
which is they've heard the opposite over and over

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:07.000
and nobody changes their minds instantly

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:11.000
because I tell them something.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:15.000
And it can be mistaken for unwarranted optimism.

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:17.000
It sounds like I'm saying,

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:20.000
oh, everything's fine, don't worry, we don't have to do anything.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.000
So that's what I said in the talk.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:26.000
I find myself I need to say three things at the same time.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:29.000
And one of them is things are getting better,

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:32.000
but also things are still very bad.

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:35.000
But also we can continue to make progress

00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:37.000
on those very bad things.

00:51:37.000 --> 00:51:39.000
Which is a three-part statement,

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:42.000
and as we've already shown that probably people are forgetting

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:44.000
the second two parts almost immediately.

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:45.000
Exactly.

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:49.000
Yeah, it's hard to get all of the pieces

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:51.000
into your head at the same time

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:53.000
to understand these more complex ideas.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:55.000
Listen.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:58.000
How do you respond to arguments

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:01.000
that like on average the world is improving,

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:04.000
but at the same time our existential risk is increasing

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:09.000
because the tails of the distribution are increasing?

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:11.000
I think that's actually two things.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:14.000
The existential risk and the tails of the distribution.

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:16.000
I think the second part is not true.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:19.000
The tails are generally going in good directions.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:22.000
There are examples of groups of people

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:26.000
There are examples of greater inequality,

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:29.000
but those are more often coming by the top,

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:32.000
moving very far to the right.

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:35.000
Usually the bottom is also improving,

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:37.000
but more slowly.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:40.000
So I don't think that there are other than,

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:44.000
as I said, short-term localized places where things get worse.

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:46.000
By and large on large scales,

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:49.000
we are all making progress.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:53.000
And especially if we look at things like extreme poverty

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:55.000
and meeting basic human needs,

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.000
we are doing that much better now

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:01.000
than at any previous time in the history of humanity.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:08.000
I think you are 100% correct

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:11.000
that we under-celebrate the advances we have made,

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:14.000
but it's a fallacy that just because we've solved problems in the past

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.000
that we will in the future.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.000
And I think you are gaslighting younger generations

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:22.000
who face real challenges other generations have not had to face.

00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:26.000
Okay, so it's a fallacy in the logical sense,

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:28.000
which is just because something happened in the past,

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:31.000
I can't prove that it will happen in the future.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:33.000
That's the problem of induction.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:35.000
I can't solve the problem of induction,

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:38.000
but I can reason from evidence.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.000
And I can say probabilistically

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:44.000
that processes that have been successful in the past

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:47.000
are likely, not provably,

00:53:47.000 --> 00:53:50.000
but likely to continue to be successful.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:52.000
And if we look at the last 100 years

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:54.000
and look at what has worked,

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
we should do more of that.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:58.000
And so, no, it's not a mathematical proof.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:01.000
It is an assertion from evidence.

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:03.000
Can I have a follow-up to that?

00:54:03.000 --> 00:54:06.000
How much of this do you think is shaped by your outlook

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:10.000
as a white male and the privilege that we get from that?

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:13.000
Yeah, my life is going pretty well.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:15.000
So, and that is, I think, one of the reasons

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:18.000
that people get angry when I say this,

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.000
because I'm in a very privileged position.

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:23.000
And, you know, that's true as a white male.

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:25.000
That is true as an American.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.000
I am educated and affluent.

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:29.000
I have every advantage in the world.

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:32.000
So I do understand why it could be off-putting

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:36.000
for me to stand up here and say how wonderful everything is.

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:40.000
But the reason I go to data

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:44.000
is to show that it's really not just for me.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:46.000
It is long-term trends.

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:49.000
It is almost every region of the world.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:51.000
It is almost every country in the world.

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:56.000
It is getting better for almost everybody

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:58.000
almost all the time.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:00.000
You know, not just me.

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:04.000
Yeah, I think many of these questions

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:07.000
kind of come down to this, like,

00:55:07.000 --> 00:55:09.000
like, how much do you believe?

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:11.000
How much do you trust what you believe

00:55:11.000 --> 00:55:13.000
and go and find data to support that?

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:16.000
And how much do you trust, like, the data

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:20.000
and then update your beliefs in the face of that?

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:22.000
So, like, how do you think about, like,

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
how do you update your, like, updating your beliefs,

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.000
changing your beliefs is hard.

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:28.000
Like, how do you do it?

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:31.000
Like, what's some belief that data has changed your mind on?

00:55:33.000 --> 00:55:35.000
I think, you know, fundamentally, I am curious.

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:39.000
When I get a new data set, that is a good day for me.

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:41.000
All of these surveys that I've been following,

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:43.000
I've been following them for years,

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:45.000
and when they release new data,

00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:47.000
that's a week of my life that I'm going to spend

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:49.000
exploring that data.

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:51.000
And I'm going to be surprised a lot,

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:54.000
and I enjoy that more when I'm surprised

00:55:54.000 --> 00:55:55.000
than when I'm not.

00:55:55.000 --> 00:55:58.000
I think, yeah, there's always confirmation bias,

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:01.000
but, you know, I don't feel good when I see data

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:03.000
that just tells me what I already knew.

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:07.000
I feel excited when I see something new that surprised me,

00:56:07.000 --> 00:56:09.000
and that's the first thing that I want to put in my blog

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:11.000
and share with everybody.

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:15.000
So I do think fundamental scientific curiosity

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:18.000
and wanting to know and wanting to know the truth

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:21.000
is at least a partial antidote to confirmation bias.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:27.000
So we have, like, a minute left,

00:56:27.000 --> 00:56:30.000
and I'm going to go on the record and say

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:32.000
I don't want to end the last question

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:34.000
on being a bummer,

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:38.000
so I am going to skip a few of these questions.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:40.000
Sorry, people.

00:56:40.000 --> 00:56:42.000
I want to end this on a kind of happy note.

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:43.000
Let me ask people.

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:46.000
So, I mean, you all just asked me to reflect

00:56:46.000 --> 00:56:49.000
on whether my outlook reflects where I'm coming from.

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:52.000
So for people, if what I said is off-putting

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:54.000
and you're sending these questions,

00:56:54.000 --> 00:56:57.000
and I appreciate that, and come talk to me more,

00:56:57.000 --> 00:56:59.000
let's talk about this,

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.000
but also ask yourself the same question,

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:05.000
and I'm genuinely curious to know

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:10.000
why do you feel that way?

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:12.000
And maybe we can talk about that.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:14.000
Should we do a show of hands of, like,

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:18.000
who is feeling, like, genuinely optimistic about the future

00:57:18.000 --> 00:57:21.000
versus pessimistic about the future?

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:24.000
I'm not sure I want to put people on the spot.

00:57:24.000 --> 00:57:26.000
We can have everyone close their eyes

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:30.000
so they can't see the results.

00:57:31.000 --> 00:57:32.000
Definitely.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:38.000
This is really high-quality data collection.

00:57:38.000 --> 00:57:41.000
Okay, I'm still going to find you, like, one.

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:42.000
Okay, here's a gimme.

00:57:42.000 --> 00:57:44.000
Let's finish on this.

00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:47.000
What advice do you have for new data scientists?

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:48.000
Well, learn Python.

00:57:48.000 --> 00:57:53.000
No.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:56.000
No, I do want to go back to the list that I had there

00:57:56.000 --> 00:57:58.000
of open science resources.

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:02.000
That is your toolkit for doing data science,

00:58:02.000 --> 00:58:07.000
and it starts with open data and open software,

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:10.000
and that certainly includes both R and Python.

00:58:10.000 --> 00:58:11.000
Great.

